SIMPLE: metropolitan
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Metropolitan
<hw>Met`ro*pol"i*tan</hw> <pr>(?; 277)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L.
<ets>metropolitanus</ets>: cf. F.
<ets>m⟦eacute⟧tropolitain</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Of or
pertaining to the capital or principal city of a country; <as>as,
<ex>metropolitan</ex> luxury</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Eccl.)</fld> <def>Of, pertaining to, or
designating, a metropolitan or the presiding bishop of a country or
province, his office, or his dignity; <as>as, <ex>metropolitan</ex>
authority</as>.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧Bishops <xex>metropolitan</xex>.⟦rdquo⟧
<rj><au>Sir T. More.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Metropolitan</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Metropolitan
<hw>Met`ro*pol"i*tan</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[LL.
<ets>metropolitanus</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The superior or
presiding bishop of a country or province.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Lat. Church.)</fld> <def>An archbishop.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Gr. Church)</fld> <def>A bishop whose see is a
civil metropolis. His rank is intermediate between that of an archbishop
and a patriarch; <as>as, the <ex>metropolitan</ex> of
Constantinople</as>.</def> <rj><au>Hook.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Metropolitanate</ent>⟦br⟧
